<LP>
   CHRYSLER AND GM raised prices on most cars and some
trucks, following Ford's lead. The unusual midyear action
reflects Detroit's desire to increase revenues amid weak
sales. The Big Three also hope an increase now will soften
the appearance of further price rises when 1991 models come
out this fall.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   General Instrument has held recent talks with Forstmann
Little, which sources say is interested in a buy-out that
could top $1.1 billion. Barring some last-minute snag, an
announcement of some transaction could occur this week.
   ---
   Kay Jewelers is expected to receive a friendly offer from
Ratners Group, an aggressively expanding British jewelry
chain.
   ---
   Some 155 failed S&amp;Ls were sold in the second quarter,
exceeding the Resolution Trust Corp.'s target. The rapid
sales of the thrifts boosted morale at the bailout agency,
but blew a hole in the federal budget.
   ---
   Time Warner sued Pathe Communications for $100 million,
charging "willful, wanton and malicious" breach of contract
in the collapse of its funding pact for Pathe's proposed $1.3
billion merger with MGM/UA.
   ---
   Securities firms' underwriting profits in the first half
plunged to their lowest level in five years, despite a rising
volume of new issues.
   ---
   Farm prices fell 1.3% in June from the previous month as
prices of hogs, wheat and soybeans slipped. Despite the
decline, hog prices remain far higher than a year ago.
   ---
   Campbell Soup will sell several businesses, close three
plants and take a charge of $247 million as it extends a 1989
restructuring program.
   ---
   Sales of new homes edged up 0.4% in May after a five-month
decline, but failed to spark any optimism about the strength
of the housing industry.
   ---
   Junk bonds posted a total return of 4.31% in the second
quarter, indicating the high-risk bonds could be climbing out
of their deep hole.
   ---
   Robert Campeau and National Bank of Canada were mum about
whether he met the payment deadline to retrieve his Campeau
Corp. securities seized by the bank.
   ---
   Arco Chemical's purchase of certain Union Carbide assets
has run into an obstacle with the FTC.
   ---
   The U.S. can prohibit Capital Cities/ABC from broadcasting
the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, a federal judge ruled.
